<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-677-747  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 677 747.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE: Work-Group Computing Report  Dec 10 1990 v1 n29 p11(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Word publishing: Describe Inc. chooses Windows 3.0 over Unix inmulti-user technology port.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Describe Inc. (Product development).andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (Computerprograms).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentWord Processing SoftwareCompatibility.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DeScribe Inc. will port its OS/2 Presentation Manager word publishingtechnology to the Windows 3.0 environment.andM;This is the same technology on which the internationally acclaimed DeScribe -Word Publisher is based and can be expected to shake up both the wordprocessing and desktop publishing niches in the DOS WINDOWS marketplace.andM;DeScribe's first WINDOWS 3.0 product is expected to be released during thesecond quarter of 1991.andM;&quot;Several times a year, we look at the question of multiple platforms.andP;  Thistime, we looked at the effort involved in moving our technology to WINDOWS3.0, various flavors of UNIX, and the Macintosh O/S versus the potentialreturn on investment.andP;  When we balanced the equation, potential WINDOWS 3.0market size won over UNIX.andM;&quot;It is the right time for DeScribe to expand, so we are proceeding withWINDOWS development.andP;  Expect a similar announcement about UNIX and any otherpopular and powerful operating system in the future,&quot; said Clif Whalen, vicepresident of marketing for DeScribe Inc.andM;&quot;The decision to port to Microsoft WINDOWS gives DeScribe broader penetrationof the corporate market.andP;  IBM's SAA vision is enterprise-wide distributeddatabases.andP;  Microsoft wants developers to provide seamless applicationtechnology across combined WINDOWS andamp; OS/2 networks.andP;  DeScribe's strategytakes advantage of both,&quot; said Allan Katzen, chief executive officer andpresident of DeScribe Inc.andM;&quot;Do not misinterpret this announcement as DeScribe is abandoning OS/2.andP;  LikeIBM, we are firmly committed to OS/2 and know that it is the operating systemof the 90s.andP;  Rather this is the natural expansion of a successful product toa second platform,&quot; said Katzen.andM;DeScribe -- Word Publisher 2.0 satisfies networked multi-user functionalitydemanded by large corporations.andP;  Shipping internationally since September of1989, DeScribe is the first word processor for OS/2 Presentation Manager.andM;It bridges the gap between word processing and desktop publishing bycombining advanced word processing functions, powerful desktop publishingfeatures, and extensive drawing capabilities in one easy to use package.andM;Server packages (which can be loaded on stand-alone workstations forindividual use) list for $595.andP;  Client packages list for $250.andP;  Multi-packsare available for quantity purchase.andP;  Twenty-three foreign language, legal,medical, biographical, and scientific dictionary options are available for$149.95 each.andM;For further information, contact Clif Whalen at DeScribe Inc., Sacramento,CA, 916/646-1111.andO;</TEXT></DOC>